A cute bat to charm it's way onto your key-ring, or in my case, as a zipper pull.

No support required for the regular Bat Charm but support is required for the Double-sided Bat Charm.

1) Sketch
I sketched out a 2D design so that I got exactly the shape/style I wished and scanned it into a jpg.
2) Solidworks
Using the imported jpg, I modeled up the image with different extrusion heights acting as my cartoon lines that defined the individual shapes and features of my drawing. I exported the file as an STL. (Solidworks file is available) Using Solidworks gave me better control over the overall size of my charm, as well as the size of the hole that I could slip a keyring onto.
3) Meshmixer
Importing the STL from Solidworks, I then smoothed out the shapes so they were less stepped and had a more organic form. I also used Meshmixer to flip the shape, so it's repeated on the back for the double-sided version.

title: Self Watering Planter
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a self-watering (aka bottom irrigation) planter. It can easily be scaled to fit your space and plant, although 50% is probably the realistic minimum size. The full size version works well on a window sill.

This is three-piece print is designed to print well on any 3d printer without supports. If you have it, it is a good idea to use a second color for the float to make it more visible.

Once it's printed:

  1. insert some short lengths of synthetic cord through the holes on the top piece to wick up water from the bottom piece. I used synthetic clothes line. The lines should be long enough to rest on the bottom when the pieces are stacked. Knot the lines at the top of each hole.

  2. Fill the top piece with your potting mix and plant. Stack it on the bottom piece and water the potting mix from the top piece until it is fully saturated. Complete filling the bottom piece from its fill spout. Leave a few millimeters unfilled.

  3. Put the float on top of the water in the fill spout. Once the float sinks to the bottom it is time to pull the float out and rewater through the fill spout.

Printed full size and with 5 wicks this planter will keep potting soil fully moist for about a week before refilling.

description.text:
This is Yet Another Dice Tower for board games.
However this one is better! The thing about rolling dice is that you get to feel like you have some control over the outcome, via your rolling. Even though we all know you don't. But it's hard to just intellect away your instincts. Dropping dice through a static tower is certainly a good randomizer but you just don't get the same visceral joy and perceived control as you do when you throw the bones yourself.

So this is the best compromise! It's a dice tower that will fully tumble the dice, however you have a large adjustable dial that you can use to bang, toss, and tweak the roll to your need. The dial controls that angle of attack for an internal shelf. That drastically affects how much the dice bounce and roll internally. No matter what the result is randomized, but you have control over the inputs to the randomization.

Give it a shot!

This is a V1 product. It needs some tweaking.

title: Prime Numbers - a physical proof that they are 6N+/-1 after 3

description.text:
This object has 6 sides and counts from 1 to 60 from top to bottom. The prime numbers are cut all the way through the wall so they stand out. Upon inspection, one will notice that the 1 column and the 5 column have all of the prime numbers after 3. Why is that?

Hopefully this is useful for teachers, students and math enthusiasts. It is also a useful bucket for knickknacks, pens, pencils, tools, and other junk on my desk. (prime junk).

Discussion Points on primes:

  • Primes and Remainders go together like Cause and Effect. Is this true?
  • Heard of Twin Primes? (primes are often separated by two) Can the 6N+/-1 rule help you see how that is true? (if you don't count 2 and 3)
  • Are there an infinite number of primes?
  • If primes are infinite then what percent of all numbers to infinity are prime?
    And finally:
  • Can you prove that every even number greater than 2 is the sum of two primes? If you can, you've solved the infamous Goldbach's conjecture. This is one of math's greatest unsolved puzzles. I'm betting that a 3D Printing junkie will solve it - if only we can get the perfect fidget toy to help us focus.

title: Swivel filament guide, the best got better !

description.text:
See also the two materials version (more difficult to make though) : by http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2318909

I just got a piece of flexible filament (black NinjaFlex) I wanted to try. No point wasting it to make test cubes and therefore I decided for a printed version of my filament guide published here : http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1853322 that has well guided a few kg of filament over the last months.

This swivel guide is far simpler and more effective due to its low mass and elasticity than the ones using bearings or a single ball. The PTFE tube helps reduce friction.

The stl is different from the part shown because I realized it would be better to give the max flex in the Z axis to smooth the sudden traction/retraction due to the extruder and carriage displacement.

It is also suited to produce a part with two kinds of filament. The flex for the base and the rest in PETG for example. The PETG would give a firmer grip on the 8mm smooth rod.
Needs some tweaking to make with one extruder as I have to measure the required flex length and join it to the PETG filament. Besides I am running short of flexible filament !

Smoothen and round with abrasive the flexible portion to reduce stress concentration that could lead to premature failure. You can also reduce the flexible part by grinding the sides to make it more flexible if required. You can see in the picture I cut half of it. This filament is surprisingly strong.

Flare both side of the 4mm PTFE tube after installation.

title: Catan frame border with harbor tiles (base game and Seafarers)

description.text:
I was looking for a Catan border with harbor tiles that could be used in all the different scenarios. JAWong's border only has fixed harbor positions, while I loved the details of them. Other versions also don't allow for non-standard harbor positions or are based on water hex tiles instead of the "new version" frame border. By letting go of the standard Catan harbor tile size, I could transfer the ship and dock to the harbor tiles. This way there are no docks or whatever showing when there is not a harbor at a specific position. The border allows for the harbors to be placed at every possible position for the game.

My printer is somewhat inaccurate, so I needed to file the frame pieces to snap together. I ended up printing the harbors at 98%.

WHAT YOU NEED
Base game:
6 x border-v2.stl. If you are planning on printing Seafarers: 4 x border-v2.stl and 2 x border-v2-forHex.stl.
4 x harbor-generic.stl
1 x harbor for every resource

Seafarers:
2 x border-withHex.stl (these do fit with the regular 'border-v2.stl', but 'border-v2-forHex' is a better fit)
2 x border-extShort.stl
2 x border-extLong.stl
1 x harbor-generic.stl
7 x sea hex with harbor cutout to play all the scenarios described in the booklet. Print variants with islands as you wish. I printed one extra to be sure.

Base game 5-6 players:
4 x border-extShort.stl. If you plan on printing Seafarers, I think you only need 2 of these.
1 x harbor-generic.stl. Not necessary if you also print Seafarers
1 x harbor-wool.stl (I think, needs checking)

Seafarers 5-6 players:
2 x border-extLong.stl

Harbor STLs still look buggy, will look into that. However, I was able to print them as-is without any problems.
